However, when the lungs are used and it is time for the passages spoken of to be closed, then these differences in the ventricles begin to appear, since the right pumps only through the lungs, but the lef t through the whole body.

There are also so-called braces in the heart, many fleshy and fibrous bands, which Aristotle calls nerves (De. Respirat. & De Part. Animal„ Lib. 3). They are stretched partly from place to place, and partly in the walls and septum, where they form little pits. Little muscles are concealed in these furrows which are added to assist in a more power- ful contraction of the heart and a more vigorous expulsion of blood.⁵ Like the elever and elaborate arrangement of ropes on a ship‚ they help the heart to contract in every direction, driving blood more fully and forcibly from the ventricles.
